duplicate of the above, unlinked and joined at shared path node,
then duplicated again and set to stroke widths (with X as the exact width to make

Split both copies at 6 nodes each to obtain 7 pieces that don't self-intersect;
"Stroke to Path" every piece, then "Difference" the white and black parts,
obtaining just the black parts (with some infinitesimal junk at the split points).
Manually draw polygons and use "Difference" to cut out the unwanted black parts
(note: I was slightly inconsistent about which parts of the doubled-up boundaries
I deleted)
Manually repair the six split points, as follows: First "Break Apart" everything
(which means the object is now split at the manual cuts from the last step,
as well as the six split points), then rejoin the split points by manually breaking
the extra edges and joining the duplicated nodes.
Union, removing all the remaining evidence of how I accomplished my trickery
For the small symbol:
Customized copy of the source above (likewise a source/clone pair)
As above, except with 0.3 instead of 0.45, and black on the inside instead of the outside.
Split and "Stroke to Path", as above, but don't "Difference" yet,
because this time we're keeping a different part..
Cut away the bridges (which, this time, is just "Difference" operations
between the white and black parts themselves, no extra boxes needed except to disambiguate)
Discard the white parts and right tail
Cut off the left tail (this required copying the uncut version of one of the black pieces to
define the edge using Difference ops)
Union and manually mend the split points
